Applying a filter to a vowel¶

The difference equation is $y[n] = x[n] - x[n-1]$. We want to find a (2,1) vector $v$ that, when used as a filter in convolution with $x$, generates the same values as the difference equation. Convolution is an element-wise operation that will fill the $y$ output vector as such: $y[i] = x[i]v[0] + x[i-1]v[1]$. If $v[0] = -1$ and $v[1] = 1$, this is equivalent to the difference equation.

So the equivalent impulse response for $y[n] = x[n] - x[n-1]$ is $[-1,1]$.

To check the above, I applied both the difference equation and the impulse response to the loaded waveform. The values match, so the impulse response and difference equation are equivalent.

In [ ]:
x, _ = librosa.load('./steadyStateVowel.wav', sr=16000)
f = np.array([-1, 1])
y = np.convolve(x, f)

To check the equivalency of my impulse equation to the difference equation, I made another numpy array whose result is the difference equation applied to $x$. Because convolution applies partially to the first and last elements in a way that the difference equation does not capture, I simply appended those elements appropriately. I then took the sum of all the differences between the two arrays and found that the two arrays are equivalent numerically.

In [ ]:
difference_equation = lambda x: np.array([x[0]] + [x[i] - x[i-1] for i in range(1, len(x))])
diff = np.append(difference_equation(x), -x[len(x)-1])
print(sum(diff - y))

0.0

When we apply to the Digital Fourier Transform directly to an entire sentence, the DFT treats the entire sentence as a single entity. This means that it assumes the signal is stationary across the entire duration of the sentence. The result would not be able to be analyzed in any meaningful way. The Short Time Fourier Transform analyzes the signal in windows, where each window has the Fourier Transform applied individually. This makes the STFT more suitable for analyzing signals with changing characteristics, like entire sentences.

Compared to the unfiltered version of the steady state vowel, the filtered version sounds tinny. This is often the result of a high-pass filter, which filters out low frequencies and passes through high frequencies. This makes sense given our filter, because if there is not a big difference between $x[n]$ and $x[n-1]$ because they are both small (thus, low frequency), the power will be small. However, if there is a big difference between $x[n]$ and $x[n-1]$, where one is a high frequency and one is low, the power will be large. So this type of filter emphasizes big differences in frequency and de-emphasizes small differences in frequency. High frequencies are thus emphasized and low frequencies are de-emphasized.

Taking the log of the power spectrogram makes it readable. The third dimension (amplitude) in the first graph had a wide range of possible values, and this large range made it difficult to distinguish the lower ends of the amplitude spectrum. However, this is where the information we want to view lies. By taking the log, we compress the range so that smaller variations are now distinguishable.

$\begin{aligned}\text{Number of samples} &= \text{window length} \times \text{sampling rate} \\ &= 0.025 \text{ seconds} \times 16000 \text{ samples per second } \\ &= 400 \text{ samples} \end{aligned} $

There are 400 samples in a 25 ms window.

plt.figure()

Out[ ]:

The previous log spectrogram does not have much time or frequency resolution at all. It appears choppy, as if the window length is too long to fully capture the minute changes in the signal. The second spectrogram is much clearer. We can see where there may be fricatives versus vowels versus no speech sounds.

I looked up the default settings for librosa.stft using the librosa documentation, and it appears the default window length is 93ms at a sample rate of 22050Hz. This is much longer than our window length is 25ms, which explains the lack of time resolution in the first spectrogram.

In [ ]:
win_spectrogram = np.log(np.abs(librosa.stft(x, win_length=120, n_fft=128))**2)

plt.figure()
librosa.display.specshow(win_spectrogram, x_axis='time', y_axis='linear')
plt.colorbar()
Out[ ]:
<matplotlib.colorbar.Colorbar at 0x7fbd7f127190>

We lose the horizontal striations from the first spectrogram and gain vertical striations, which suggests an improvement in time resolution and a decrease in frequency resolution. Since we kept our sampling rate the same, the window length in seconds for the second spectrogram is

$120 = x \cdot 16000$

$x = 0.0075$

Because the window size is much smaller (~8ms vs 25ms), this spectrogram has better time resolution than the first spectrogram. When the window size is smaller, small variations between time frames are more easily captured. However, in gaining time resolution, we lose frequency resolution. Thus the two spectrograms show the two types of resolution we might care about when looking at a spectrogram -- frequency and time.

The first spectrogram (with a window size of 400) is narrowband, and the second spectrogram (with a window size of 120) is broadband. Narrowband spectrograms have better frequency resolution, resulting in horizontal bands that distinguish frequencies. We can see this in the first spectrogram. Broadband spectrograms have better time resolution, resulting in vertical bands that distinguish periods of time. We can see this in the second spectrogram.

Speech Recognition with MFCCs¶

Here are three reasons why unsupervised learning may be preferred over supervised learning:

  • If labeling is too expensive or otherwise unfeasible for the data that will be used in the learning algorithm, unsupervised learning may be more appropriate.

  • Unsupervised learning is useful for identifying anomalies. Anomalies are not expected patterns and thus cannot be labeled ahead of time, so unsupervised learning is more appropriate.

  • Clustering is an unsupervised learning technique that can be useful for exploring the structure and nature of the data. This technique can be used to uncover previously unknown clusters. Since the clusters are not known beforehand, the data could not be labeled for the learning task, making this an appropriate use case for unsupervised learning.

In [ ]:
def get_mfcc(input):
    output = []
    for file in input: 
        x, _ = librosa.load(file)
        mfcc = librosa.feature.mfcc(y=x, sr=16000, n_mfcc=8, n_fft=512, win_length=400, hop_length=160)
        output.append(mfcc)
        
    return output 

zeroes_mfcc = get_mfcc(zeroes)
ones_mfcc = get_mfcc(ones)

print(len(zeroes_mfcc))
print(len(ones_mfcc))

144
146

After some experimentation, I chose the frame number $21$. It is far enough from the beginning of the files to not have some instances of silence, and it is close to the initial sounds of each word, which are very different acoustically.

In [ ]:
zeroes_frames = [np.expand_dims(mfcc[:, 21], axis=0) for mfcc in zeroes_mfcc]
ones_frames = [np.expand_dims(mfcc[:, 21], axis=0) for mfcc in ones_mfcc]

X = np.concatenate(zeroes_frames + ones_frames, axis=0)

y = np.array([0] * len(zeroes_frames) + [1] * len(ones_frames))

print(X.shape)

Out[ ]:
1.0

My model is performing with a 1.0 score, meaning that it never misclassifies any of the zeroes or ones. I experimented with some other frame numbers before finding this model, some near 0 and some near 35. The frame numbers close to 0 were very poor, while the frame numbers closer to 35 were near 1.0. The frame numbers close to 0 were likely picking up differences in speech onset time, which do not help with classification. The frame numbers closer to 35 were likely picking up differences in formants between the vowels. This is helpful for classification but not as helpful as the difference between a fricative and a liquid.
